paragraphs.text: To give something to many people for free
Starbucks is giving out free coffee to the first hundred customers today! [audio:phrases_verbs_give_out_2]
There were some people by the library giving out brochures about financial aid. [audio:phrases_verbs_give_out_3]
Sorry I don’t have time to chat, I’m already running late for my dentist appointment. [audio:phrases_verbs_running_late_2]
Mark told me that he’s running a bit late, so he’ll be here in an hour. [audio:phrases_verbs_running_late_3]
I always pay my rent on time, so why are you kicking me out of my apartment? [audio:phrases_verbs_on_time_2]
The buses never come on time. It’s faster to take the subway. [audio:phrases_verbs_on_time_3]
เปิด / ปิด. For electronics, you can’t use the words ‘open / close’ - you must use 'turn off / turn on'
Do you mind turning off the lights and turning on the lamp?  [audio:phrases_verbs_turn_on_off_2]
Why did you turn the TV off? I was watching a movie! [audio:phrases_verbs_turn_on_off_3]
Are you hot? I’ll turn on the AC. [audio:phrases_verbs_turn_on_off_4]
Pailin: Could you drop off this package at the post office? But ask for express shipping, not regular shipping. [audio:phrases_verbs_got_it_2]Luke: Okay, got it.
Luke: Make sure you leave the key under the mat before you leave. [audio:phrases_verbs_got_it_3]Pailin: Got it.
An exclamation to show that something is impressive, excellent, or wonderful
Luke: I got the job! [audio:phrases_verbs_awesome_2]Pailin: What! That’s awesome!
Luke: I was able to get my shift covered, so I can go with you guys to Mexico. [audio:phrases_verbs_awesome_3]
Pailin: Awesome! We should book our flights this week then.
Oh my God, I just won two free tickets for a trip to Cancun! [audio:phrases_verbs_oh_my_god_2]
(link xx) See more uses of ‘Oh my God’
An informal phrase to reassure someone that it’s not a problem, or it’s fine
Do you have sunscreen I can use? If not, no worries. I can stop by a store to get some. [audio:phrases_verbs_no_worries_2]
Pailin: Sorry I’m a little late! [audio:phrases_verbs_no_worries_3]
Luke: No worries, we just arrived too.
To submit an application for a job, a loan, or a school
I applied for a job at Google, but I don’t think I’ll get it. [audio:phrases_verbs_apply_for_2]
A casual way to say you will go to a bar or restaurant and buy a drink, usually an alcoholic one
We’re getting drinks after work to celebrate Mark’s birthday. Do you wanna join? [audio:phrases_verbs_get_a_drink_2]
Let’s get a drink and catch up, since I haven’t seen you in a while. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_a_drink_3]
Used to show that someone’s proposal is a good one
Pailin: We’ll probably meet up tomorrow morning at 10AM. How does that sound? [audio:phrases_verbs_that_sounds_great_2]
Luke: That sounds great, see you guys then.
Said when you are passing something to someone
Here you go, these are the keys to my apartment. [audio:phrases_verbs_here_you_go_2]
Luke: Pai, did you bring that book I wanted to borrow? [audio:phrases_verbs_here_you_go_3]
A sound made to show you’re thinking
Luke: What time did we leave the house? [audio:phrases_verbs_umm_2]
Pailin: Umm, I think we left around 6:50.
I love cats, but I’m allergic to them. [audio:phrases_verbs_allergic_to_2]
Dara is allergic to shellfish and peanuts. [audio:phrases_verbs_allergic_to_3]
To eat small amounts of food for fun, rather than eating a whole meal
I like to snack on popcorn while watching a movie. [audio:phrases_verbs_snack_on_2]
We can snack on these crackers until dinner is ready. [audio:phrases_verbs_snack_on_3]
A word to show you’ve changed your mind
Let’s have spaghetti for dinner. Actually, let’s make a salad. I ate spaghetti for lunch. [audio:phrases_verbs_actually_2]
The show starts at 8, so let’s get there at 7:30. Actually, wait, we should get there earlier. There might be a line. [audio:phrases_verbs_actually_3]
To continue using or doing something, or to not change a decision
Mmm, the pistachio ice cream is good, but I think I’ll stick with my usual chocolate flavor. [audio:phrases_verbs_stick_with_2]
I’ve given it a lot of thought, but I’m sticking with my decision to quit nursing school. [audio:phrases_verbs_stick_with_3]
It’s getting late, I think I’ll head home now. [audio:phrases_verbs_head_home_2]
We should start heading home before the traffic gets too bad. [audio:phrases_verbs_head_home_3]
To hit something with force, usually by accident
Emily wasn’t paying attention and bumped into a table. She spilled her drink everywhere. [audio:phrases_verbs_bump_into_2]
This guy on the subway kept bumping into me. I think he was trying to pickpocket me. [audio:phrases_verbs_bump_into_3]
(link xx) See more uses of ‘Bump into’
Ow! You stepped on my toe! [audio:phrases_verbs_ouch_3]
A very informal expression used for regret
Man, I really should have studied more for that test. [audio:phrases_verbs_man1_2]
An expression to show sympathy for someone else’s bad luck
Luke: I didn’t get the job. They told me I’m not qualified for the position. [audio:phrases_verbs_oh_no1_2]
Pailin: Oh no! Sorry to hear that.
(link xx) See more uses of ‘Oh no’
A filler word at the beginning of a sentence to transition to a new topic
Pailin: I’m so sad the show was canceled tonight. [audio:phrases_verbs_well_2]
Luke: Well, we can still do something. Let’s try that new restaurant down the street.
ขายหมดแล้ว
The tickets for Coachella sold out after just an hour! [audio:phrases_verbs_sold_out_2]
The store was all sold out of that gummy bear brand that you like, so I chose a different brand. [audio:phrases_verbs_sold_out_3]
Said when expressing mild anger or disappointment
Darn it! Our Uber driver already drove away. We took too long to come out. [audio:phrases_verbs_darn_it_2]
Darn, it’s starting to rain. I guess we should postpone our hike, then. [audio:phrases_verbs_darn_it_3]
To pay for items at a register
Are you ready to check out now? [audio:phrases_verbs_check_out1_2]
Did you find everything you need? Great, you can check out at the front of the store. [audio:phrases_verbs_check_out1_3]
(link xx) See more uses of ‘Check out’
An informal phrase to reassure someone that it’s not an issue or you’re happy to help after they thank you
Pailin: Could you print these documents for me? [audio:phrases_verbs_no_problem_2]
Luke: Sure, no problem. I’ll do it right now.
Pailin: Thanks for dropping me off! [audio:phrases_verbs_no_problem_3]
Luke: No problem, it was on my way to work.
My eyes hurt after looking at my computer all day. [audio:phrases_verbs_look_at_2]
Let’s look at the map to see what coffee shops are around here. [audio:phrases_verbs_look_at_3]
To match with something or to look attractive with something else
The red dress goes great with these black heels. [audio:phrases_verbs_go_great_with_3]
Said when you can’t believe something
So they wouldn’t give you a refund even though you had your receipt? That’s crazy! [audio:phrases_verbs_thats_crazy_2]
Luke: Someone broke into my car, and they took everything except for my laptop! [audio:phrases_verbs_thats_crazy_3]
A filler phrase used to clarify or emphasize a previous statement
I liked the movie. I mean, it was a bit long, but I loved the plot. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_mean_2]
Pailin: The coffee shop closes in 20 minutes. Should we go somewhere else? [audio:phrases_verbs_i_mean_3]
Luke: I mean, we can still get a coffee and sit for a little bit.
What jobs have you had in the past?
